  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The objective of this prospective study is to evaluate the prevalence of neurocognitive
      impairments in HIV infected patients comparing patients with and without HAART. Recent
      studies have demonstrated a specific HIV infected patients neurocognitive disorders profile.
      These cognitive disorders concern primarily information processing speed, memory recall,
      attentional abilities, work related memory, executive functions, and psychometrical speed.
      This cognitive profile is similar to another highly documented one, described for another
      central nervous system disease (CNS): multiple sclerosis. In both CNS diseases, the earliest
      and most severe disorder is the one related to the information processing speed. For the
      multiple sclerosis patients, a short cognitive test (SDMT) is actually used not only to
      identify cognitive disorders presence, but also in order to predict a long term disability
      worsening. A digital version of this test (CSCT), has recently been developed in order to
      make this early evaluation easier. We hypothesize that CSCT alteration would also predict
      HAND, in HIV infected patients. A complete neuropsychological assessment is highly time and
      personal consuming. This short (approximatively 2 minutes) digital test would be highly
      helpful to identify patients, who will need a more extensive neuropsychological assessment.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
